&nbsp;
<h6>Step 3 - The Node.js Client Code</h6>
So now we have a form with a pretty button that accepts a picture and does nothing to it. Time to add some Node.js client code to send and receive as well as display the picture (in chat.js):
<pre>sendMediaForm.change('uploadMedia', function (e) {
 var selectedMedia = e.originalEvent.target.files[0];
 sendMedia(selectedMedia);
 });


 function sendMedia(selectedMedia) 
 {
 if (selectedMedia.name != "") {
 var reader = new FileReader();
 reader.onload = function (evt) {
 socket.emit('sendMedia', { mediaSend: evt.target.result, user: name, img: img });
 };
 reader.readAsDataURL(selectedMedia);
 }
 else {
 alert("Please Select an Image, Video or Audio File.");
 }
 }</pre>
Here we are using jQuery to trigger on the upload button of the form to call a function to emit the picture over a Socket.io socket to the Node.js server. The image is loaded by a FileReader object by calling the readAsDataURL() method.

To receive the image from the server we need to listen to the Socket.io socket for an event from the Node.js server:
<pre>socket.on('receiveMedia', function (data) {

showMessage("chatStarted");

// Display the media message
 createMediaMessage(data.user, data.img, data.mediaSend, moment());
 scrollToBottom();
 });

</pre>
This Socket.io listener waits for the "receiveMedia" message from the Node.js server and sends the data to a Javascript function to display the image to the other chat user:
<pre>// Function that creates a new media message
 function createMediaMessage(user,imgg,mediaSend,now) {

var who = '';

if (user === name) {
 who = 'me';
 }
 else {
 who = 'you';
 }

var li = $(
 '&lt;li class=' + who + '&gt;' +
 '<div class="image">' +
 '<img src=' + imgg + ' />' +
 '<b></b>' +
 '<i class="timesent"></i> ' +
 '</div>' +
 '&lt;img src=' + mediaSend + ' /&gt;' +
 '&lt;/div&gt;' +
 '&lt;/li&gt;');

// use the 'text' method to escape malicious user input
 li.find('b').text(user);

chats.append(li);

messageTimeSent = $(".timesent");
 messageTimeSent.last().text(now.fromNow());
 }</pre>
The image is embedded into the jQuery li variable which is displayed on the chat screen.
<h6>Step 4 - Node.js Server Code</h6>
FInally, the Node.js server routes the images from one client to another. We have a simple Socket.io listenser to accept images and broadcast them back to the other users in the chatroom in routes.js:
<pre>// Handle the sending of media files
 socket.on('sendMedia', function (data) {
 // When the server receives a media file, it sends it to the other person in the room.
 socket.broadcast.to(socket.room).emit('receiveMedia', { mediaSend: data.mediaSend, user: data.user, img: data.img });
 });</pre>
&nbsp;

I hope you liked this simple tutorial of how to send images with Node.js, Express and Socket.io. For the complete chatroom project please see it on my <a href="https://github.com/bmisljen/Node.js-Ultimate-Chatroom">GitHub</a>. I will post again with more updates on the project!

[caption id="attachment_115" align="alignleft" width="300"]<img class="size-medium wp-image-115" src="https://borismisljencevic.files.wordpress.com/2016/07/single-page-website.png?w=300" alt="Pull Out Menu" width="300" height="142" /> Pull Out Menu[/caption]

In this tutorial I will go over how to create a pull out sidebar menu as shown in the picture using HTML/CSS, Bootstrap and Javascript. The great thing about this menu is that it can be used on phones and tablets as well as PC's as it will resize automatically. The menu will contain items linking to different locations on your website home page and will scroll down to the section clicked on. The menu uses a <a href="http://fontawesome.io/icons/">font awesome</a> icon to display the three bars to be clicked when it is hidden. It will close when the user picks a section or when they click the "x" inside the menu. A free example of the menu incorporated in a single page website can be found at: <a href="https://github.com/bmisljen/bmisljen.github.io">https://github.com/bmisljen/bmisljen.github.io</a>. This tutorial will go over the code in that repository and will explain what is going on and what the different steps in creating the menu are.
<h5>Step 1: Getting the Project</h5>
The project is available for free at Github and can be cloned via Git into a new directory via the following command:

[code language="bash"]
git clone https://github.com/bmisljen/bmisljen.github.io.git
[/code]

Inside the startbootstrap-stylish-portfolio folder there are a few files and a few other subfolders. The index.html file is the main html home page file and the one we will be talking about most about along with the stylish-portfolio.css file in the css folder. The img folder contains graphics for the website while the fonts and font awesome folders contain libraries for the shapes and the text fonts we will be using from the Font Awesome Libraries. Finally, the js folder contains the Bootstrap and JQuery libraries which we will need to link too in our HTML files in order to use Bootstrap and HTML.

The website itself is a mock architecture business website and can be demoed at: <a href="https://bmisljen.github.io/">https://bmisljen.github.io/</a>
<h5>Step 2: HTML</h5>
The HTML code involved is quite simple. It creates a menu with a Bootstrap button and a Font Awesome icon which is toggled when the icon is clicked. Clicking the three bar icon on the screen causes the menu to pull out from the right and display the different menu sections of the page. In index.html note the following code:

[code language="html"]
    &lt;a id=&quot;menu-toggle&quot; href=&quot;#&quot; class=&quot;btn btn-dark btn-lg toggle&quot;&gt;&lt;i class=&quot;fa fa-bars&quot;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
[/code]

This creates a bootstrap dark button linked to a 3 bar "fa fa-bars" Font Awesome menu icon that toggles the sidebar menu open and closed when clicked.

[code language="html"]


&lt;nav id=&quot;sidebar-wrapper&quot;&gt;
[/code]

The "sidebar-wrapper" class contains all the CSS styling rules for the menu size, location and open and close behavior. This class will be used to house all the menu items and sections.

Inside the "sidebar-brand" styled HTML class each section is displayed as a row linking to a different Bootstrap container at different parts of the page.  In index.html you can see:

[code language="html"]

&lt;ul class=&quot;sidebar-nav&quot;&gt;
            &lt;a id=&quot;menu-close&quot; href=&quot;#&quot; class=&quot;btn btn-light btn-lg pull-right toggle&quot;&gt;&lt;i class=&quot;fa fa-times&quot;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;li class=&quot;sidebar-brand&quot;&gt;
                &lt;a href=&quot;#top&quot; onclick=$(&quot;#menu-close&quot;).click();&gt;ABC Architecture&lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;/li&gt;


&lt;li&gt;
                &lt;a href=&quot;#top&quot; onclick=$(&quot;#menu-close&quot;).click();&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;/li&gt;


&lt;li&gt;
                &lt;a href=&quot;#about&quot; onclick=$(&quot;#menu-close&quot;).click();&gt;About&lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;/li&gt;


&lt;li&gt;
                &lt;a href=&quot;#services&quot; onclick=$(&quot;#menu-close&quot;).click();&gt;Services&lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;/li&gt;


&lt;li&gt;
                &lt;a href=&quot;#portfolio&quot; onclick=$(&quot;#menu-close&quot;).click();&gt;Portfolio&lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;/li&gt;


&lt;li&gt;
                &lt;a href=&quot;#contact&quot; onclick=$(&quot;#menu-close&quot;).click();&gt;Contact&lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;/li&gt;

        &lt;/ul&gt;

[/code]

One example of a Bootstrap container to be used for a section is the "About" section:

[code language="html"]
    &lt;!-- About --&gt;

&lt;section id=&quot;about&quot; class=&quot;about&quot;&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;container&quot;&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;row&quot;&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;col-lg-12 text-center&quot;&gt;

