Finally, the "menu-toggle" and "sidebar-wrapper.active" sections are used to toggle the menu from open to closed and closed to open and to define the transition behavior:

[code language="css"]
#menu-toggle {
    z-index: 1;
    position: fixed;
    top: 0;
    right: 0;
}

#sidebar-wrapper.active {
    right: 250px;
    width: 250px;
    -webkit-transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;
    -moz-transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;
    -ms-transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;
    -o-transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;
    transition: all 0.4s ease 0s;
}
[/code]

<h5>Step 4: Javascript</h5>
[caption id="attachment_127" align="alignleft" width="156"]<img class="size-medium wp-image-127" src="https://borismisljencevic.files.wordpress.com/2016/07/menu-complete.png?w=156" alt="Completed Menu" width="156" height="300" /> Completed Menu[/caption]

So by now the menu looks great and all but it doesn't have any functionality when the menu item buttons are clicked. This is where the Javascript code comes in. There are three things that should be possible with the menu; when the 3 bar menu icon is clicked the menu should open up. Clicking the "x" in the top right should close the menu to the right. Lastly, when any one of the menu items is clicked the menu should take the user to that section of the page and close the menu as the item has been selected.

The menu opens and closes by toggling the: "sidebar-wrapper.active" class from the CSS code. This CSS class is responsible for opening and closing the menu and works like a toggle switch; on the first click it opens the menu and on the second it closes it. In index.html:

[code language="javascript"]
    &lt;!-- Include jQuery --&gt;
    &lt;script src=&quot;js/jquery.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

    &lt;!-- Bootstrap Core JavaScript --&gt;
    &lt;script src=&quot;js/bootstrap.min.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

    &lt;!-- Custom Theme JavaScript --&gt;
    &lt;script&gt;
    // Closes the sidebar menu
    $(&quot;#menu-close&quot;).click(function(e) {
        e.preventDefault();
        $(&quot;#sidebar-wrapper&quot;).toggleClass(&quot;active&quot;);
    });
    // Opens the sidebar menu
    $(&quot;#menu-toggle&quot;).click(function(e) {
        e.preventDefault();
        $(&quot;#sidebar-wrapper&quot;).toggleClass(&quot;active&quot;);
    });
[/code]

The next bit of code is slightly more complex in that it actually scrolls to the given section and closes the menu if that given section is on the current page. Otherwise if there is an incorrect attempt to scroll past the bottom of the page, the page is scrolled back to the top. Note that this function only works if the menu item is on the current page (contained in index.html as a Bootstrap container in this case):

[code language="javascript"]
 // Scrolls to the selected menu item on the page
    $(function() {
        $('a[href*=#]:not([href=#],[data-toggle],[data-target],[data-slide])').click(function() {
            if (location.pathname.replace(/^\//, '') == this.pathname.replace(/^\//, '') || location.hostname == this.hostname) {
                var target = $(this.hash);
                target = target.length ? target : $('[name=' + this.hash.slice(1) + ']');
                if (target.length) {
                    $('html,body').animate({
                        scrollTop: target.offset().top
                    }, 1000);
                    return false;
                }
            }
        });
    });

&lt;/script&gt;
[/code]

So now the menu not only looks great but it also functions well and automatically scrolls to each selected section with ease! It also closes itself when the "x" is clicked and opens when the 3 bar icon is clicked. To add items to the menu, simply add a Bootstrap container and add an item to the sidebar menu HTML and it will be scrolled to automatically when selected!
